<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Second Election Round Planned for 9-10 Apr </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2803192694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1755 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803192694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ukrainian Central Electoral Commission expects 
to hold the second round of parliamentary elections on 9 and 10 
April. This was reported to the press by the commission chairman 
Ivan Yemets. 
  However, "several district commissions suggest holding the 
second round already this week, on 2 April." In these 
circumstances the Central Commission is not going to insist on 
its opinion, Yemets said. Moreover, district commissions will 
have a chance to hold elections at a time suitable for them. 
  "They will be free to organize voting this weekend or the 
next, but 10 April is the latest possible date under the law," 
the official said. 
  According to preliminary reports from district commissions, 
47 out of 450 members of the new parliament were elected in the 
first round. Thus, a second round of voting will be held in 403 
electoral districts. 
  Fourteen of the elected members of parliament are Socialists 
and Communists. They were elected mostly in Donetsk, Lugansk 
and other eastern regions. 
  Thirteen members from Western Ukraine belong to 
national-democratic organizations. 
  There are also two members of the radical Ukrainian National 
Assembly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

