<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rukh Leader Terms Election Results Successful </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2803200494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1755 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803200494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The leader of the Ukrainian nationalist movement 
Rukh, Vyacheslav Chernovil, described the results of the first 
round of parliamentary elections in Ukraine as a success for 
democratic forces. At a news conference in Kiev Monday, he 
pointed out that candidates of Rukh and the democratic bloc had 
been either elected or passed on to the second round of the 
elections in most constituencies of the Republic. 
  "There is hope that the new Supreme Soviet will be better 
and 
it will be possible to structure it by creating factions and 
blocs," Chernovil said. He pointed out that these elections 
were more free and democratic than before. However, numerous 
violations which influenced the electors' choice in favor of the 
ruling party had been revealed, according to Chernovil. 
  "Rukh will react calmly to any change in the timing of 
Ukrainian presidential elections," Chernovil was quoted as 
saying. He added that it was ridiculous to elect the head of 
the state without defining his legislative powers beforehand. 
However, Rukh insists that the election day must be set exactly 
so that either the old, or the new parliament could pass the 
necessary laws. At the same time, Chernovil spoke against 
granting the Ukrainian president extra powers. 
  The Rukh leader believes that the results of the opinion 
polls in the Donets Basin and the Crimea will have no legal 
force. "If the leaders of the state hold firm and stick to the 
law, everything will take its course as it should in a 
democratic country," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

