<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Servicemen `Will Not Obey' Meshkov </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2803165494 Kiev UT-1 Television Network in Ukrainian 1445 
GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2803165494 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UT-1 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Ukrainian Deputy Defense Minister Ivan </F>
Bizhan by unidentified reporter; place and date not given -- 
recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Reporter] Ivan Vasilyevych, you have just 
returned from the Crimea. The most acute problem facing your 
branch is the order issued by President of the Crimean Autonomy 
[as heard] Meshkov regarding the military service of Crimean 
residents on Crimean territory. What are your impressions and 
assessments of this development? 
  [Bizhan] Your question is right. Really, it is very 
important that such a question has been raised. This is why the 
[defense] minister resolved so forcefully and quickly to send a 
group to the Crimea headed by the deputy defense minister to 
immediately, so to say, examine the situation on the spot. 
  My impressions are the following. I am very glad that our 
military structures -- including the Crimea's military 
commissar, the military commissar of Sevastopol, the command of 
our Navy and Air Force, and the 32d Corps Command -- understand 
it in such a way as they should understand: This order is 
unlawful, has no underlaying legal basis, and is not subject to 
being obeyed. They will not obey it. That is to say, it is not 
necessary today to conduct work with this commanding structure 
to elucidate the position of the defense minister. Therefore, 
after my return, I was glad to report to the defense minister 
that we have conscious and aware people there -- they are 
Ukrainian citizens, real and true, and they will comply to 
Ukraine's laws and the instructions of our supreme commander of 
the Armed Forces and the defense minister. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

