<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia, Serb Krajina Sign Six Maps </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903144794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1319 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903144794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The first six of 35 maps of troops separation were 
signed in Zagreb by negotiators representing Croatia and the 
self-proclaimed republic of Serb Krajina in their second round 
of talks that started Tuesday. The Russian diplomat who broke 
this news to INTERFAX said, however, that "the talks are 
difficult and there is no telling when the remaining documents 
will be signed." 
  The talks which are underway in the Russian Embassy in 
Zagreb 
center on a cease-fire and troops separation. Special envoys of 
the Russian and U.S. Presidents Vitaliy Churkin and Charles 
Redman are attending them as mediators as are officials of the 
UN and the International Peace Conference on Former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

