<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Work on Civil Accord Draft Agreement Completed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2803195394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1637 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The work on the draft agreement on civic peace in 
Russia was completed last Saturday and the document will soon be 
submitted to President Boris Yeltsin. This was disclosed to 
Interfax on Monday by a member of the drafting team. 
  The source said that the document suggests renouncing early 
elections, potentially destabilizing constitutional amendments 
and the politically charged comments on the events of October 
1993. 
  The draft reportedly includes the formation of a public body 
to ensure all sides observe the agreement. It should be signed 
by federal government bodies, federation members, parliamentary 
groups, political movements, public organizations and trade 
unions. 
  If the terms are violated by any party, they will be asked 
to 
leave the political arena. 
  At the initiative of the president the document was drafted 
by five working groups on the following spheres: politics, 
economy, regional and ethnic matters, culture, security. 
  Earlier on Monday a well-informed source close to the 
president told Interfax that the final text of the draft 
agreement will be handed to Yeltsin within the next few hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

