<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Statement Issued on Election `Violations' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903085294 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 0800 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903085294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Representatives of the Ukrainian public and 
political organizations in Crimea and the Crimean-Tatar National 
Movement Organization have issued a joint statement. The 
statement points out gross violations of the law in Crimea 
during the course of the election campaign and during the 
election itself. These include campaigning on the eve of 
election, the issue of several ballot papers to one person, the 
issue of ballot papers to people without identification, and 
pressure on the electoral commissions and voters exerted by 
representatives of the Rossiya bloc. The worst violation, the 
statement says, was the propaganda speech by president of 
Crimea, Yuriy Meshkov, on local television last Friday. 
  The authors of the statement are convinced that the 
situation 
in Crimea will continue to deteriorate if Yuriy Meshkov, his 
administration and the newly elected Supreme Council fail to 
work constructively to preserve peace and stability on the 
peninsula. Proceeding from this, the statement says, cooperation 
between Ukrainian and Crimean-Tatar organizations has acquired 
special significance. The Ukrainian organizations will be even 
more uncompromising in defending the interests of the Crimean 
Tatars through their central offices in Kiev and their deputies 
in Ukraine's Supreme Council. The Crimean-Tatar National 
Movement Organization will support Ukrainian organizations on 
the issues of preserving Ukraine's territorial integrity and 
consolidating Ukrainian statehood on the territory of Crimea. 

</TEXT>

