<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Between Russian, Kazakh Presidents Summed Up </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2803201594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1755 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803201594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] After the ceremony of signing Russo-Kazakh 
documents, Russian President Boris Yeltsin told Interfax that no 
political issues had been aroused around Russia's leasing the 
cosmodrome in Baykonur. 
  "The talks focused on problems concerning the maintenance of 
a city in the steppe where the cosmodrome's workers live. We 
have solved this issue. I am confident that our children and 
grandchildren will use Baykonur in the 21st century in the 
interests of both Russia and Kazakhstan," Yeltsin was quoted as 
saying. 
  For his part, Kazakh President Nursultan Nazarbayev put a 
special emphasis on Russia's important role in the development 
of Kazakhstan's scientific, technological and cultural 
potential. No speculation about Kazakhstan's alleged cooling 
towards Russia have any grounds, he added. 
  The two presidents signed four main documents out of 23 
bilateral accords adopted as a result of the summit, including 
treaties on the further enhancement of economic cooperation and 
integration, on the strategic nuclear forces temporarily 
stationed in Kazakhstan, on military cooperation and a 
memorandum on the basic principles for the resolution of issues 
related to the citizenship and the legal status of Russian and 
Kazakh citizens residing on the territory of the other state. 
  Yeltsin received letters of ratification on Kazakhstan's 
joining the non-proliferation treaty from his Kazakh counterpart. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

