<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Terms Visit Successful </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2803181794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1755 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2803181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 28 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin praised the results of Kazakh President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev's first official visit to Russia as "very successful." 
  Meeting journalists after the ceremony of signing 
Russian-Kazakh bilateral agreements in the Kremlin on Monday, 
Yeltsin described the visit as "the first and very important 
official visit by the head of the Republic of Kazakhstan to 
Russia." 
  Yeltsin said Russia and Kazakhstan signed a record number of 
bilateral agreements. The prime ministers of the two countries 
and Russian and Kazakh governmental delegations signed a total 
of 23 bilateral agreements, including on political, economic and 
military cooperation. 
  "Russia and Kazakhstan already have the basis of bilateral 
relations, namely the bilateral treaty of friendship and 
cooperation," he continued. "But this document needs to be 
developed and expanded." The Russian leader said that all the 
documents had been prepared thoroughly and long. The agreement 
on the Baykonur cosmodrome had been ironed out for nearly a year. 
  Nazarbayev stressed that his visit "sweeps away all talks 
and 
rumours about Russia's imperial activity." Both sides had 
"overcome all difficulties," he added. 
  Commenting on the agreement on Baykonur, Nazarbayev replied 
that the Kazakh side "understands how important Baykonur is for 
Russia now," added that "Kazakhstan did not want to keep it in 
its pocket." 
  Yeltsin noted that the "difficulties which emerged in this 
issue were connected not with the political aspect, but mostly 
with the technical and economic one." 
  The president explained that the latter concerned primarily 
technical and economic support for the people living in the city 
of Leninsk and servicing the cosmodrome. 
  Under the agreement, Kazakhstan will lease the cosmodrome to 
Russia for 20 years with further prolongation of the term for 
another ten years. Russia will pay 115 million U.S. dollars to 
Kazakhstan annually in lease payments. The agreement also 
considers Baykonur Russian territory for the duration of the 
lease period where all Russian laws will have equal force as in 
the rest of Russia. 
  The two presidents also signed an agreement on the 
development of economic cooperation and integration, a 
memorandum of the basic principles of resolving issues 
concerning the civil and legal status of citizens of Kazakhstan 
living in Russia and Russian citizens residing in Kazakhstan, an 
agreement on military cooperation and an agreement on strategic 
nuclear forces temporarily stationed in Kazakhstan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

