<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Snegur Calls for Strengthening Statehood </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903205194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1836 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moldovan President Mircea Snegur has said that the 
main goal of the new parliament and the whole nation should be 
strengthening the Republic's statehood. Speaking before the 
newly elected parliament Tuesday, he said society expected the 
new legislature to ensure further development and strengthening 
of the state in the interests of all its citizens, regardless of 
their origin or faith. 
  Snegur pointed out that various political forces had 
appeared 
on Moldova's political scene after the collapse of totalitarian 
rule. At the moment, they are divided into supporters of 
strengthening Moldova's statehood and independence, supporters 
of the unification with Romania and supporters of the republic's 
return to a reborn empire. 
  In the meantime, the Moldovan people firmly supported 
Moldova's development as an independent democratic state at the 
sociological poll on 6 March, Snegur said. The outcomes of the 
poll must be law for everyone, he said pointing out that "a 
state cannot be built on the basis of an idea which splits and 
polarizes society." 
  Snegur pointed to the top priority of such goals as the 
adoption of a new constitution, preservation of Moldova's 
territorial integrity, resolution of the issues of Transdniester 
and Gagauz-populated areas, democratization of society and 
enhancing economic reforms. 
  Snegur also proposed a special law be adopted against 
insulting Moldova as a state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

