<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Luchinsky Elected Parliament Speaker </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903115894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1123 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903115894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Valeriy Demidetskiy] </F>
  [Text] Kishinev 29 Mar, TASS -- Petr Luchinskiy, a leader 
of the Agrarian Democratic Party that won the preterm 
parliamentary elections in February, was elected speaker of the 
Moldovan parliament on Tuesday. He was elected by a secret 
ballot, earning 57 votes. There were 43 votes against, and two 
ballots were found invalid. 
  Luchinsky is 54 years old. In perestroika years he was first 
secretary of the Central Committee of the Moldovan Communist 
Party, secretary of the Central Committee of the Soviet 
Communist Party, CPSU. He was elected speaker of the previous 
Moldovan parliament after an acute parliamentary crisis last 
year. The parliament, torn by contradictions, had to be 
dissolved. 
  It is the first time that a Moldovan parliament has been 
formed on a multiparty basis. It will include 104 deputies. 
The Agrarian Democratic Party will have parliamentary majority, 
56 deputies. 
  Agrarians believe that the legislative body should above all 
adopt a new constitution, create a legislative base for economic 
reform, and resolve the Dniester and Gagauz problems through 
granting special legal status to these territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

