<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia To Aid DPRK in Event of `Unprovoked Aggression' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903171294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1538 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903171294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: by diplomatic </F>
correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboynikov, Igor Porshnev, Vitaliy 
Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] In keeping with the treaty between the USSR and the 
People's Democratic Republic of Korea Russia will help North 
Korea in the event of an unprovoked aggression, but will make 
the decision only on the basis of its own analysis of the 
situation. This was reported at a Tuesday briefing in Moscow by 
the Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Panov. 
  He described the current situation in the Korean peninsula 
as 
balancing on the brink of war. 
  In his opinion the recent Russian initiative to convene a 
conference of six interested countries (China, the USA, Japan, 
Russia and the two Koreas) and the United Nations and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency promotes a settlement in that 
part of the world. 
  The deputy minister stressed that Russia by no means 
questions the efforts of the UN Security Council or the IAEA. 
"However, the steps of the two organizations to normalize the 
situation in the Korean peninsula do not always produce the 
desired results", he remarked. 
  Panov announced that the Russian initiative is closely 
studied by all interested sides. "So far there have been no 
negative answers", he said. 
  In the opinion of the diplomat the conference should 
concentrate on making the peninsula a nuclear-free zone. He 
stressed that Russia and the USA agree that the conference 
should be well-prepared and discuss the membership of North 
Korea in the nuclear non-proliferation treaty, the observation 
of all safety regulations and a joint declaration of the two 
Koreas on a nuclear-free zone. 
  According to Panov, the conference could begin in Geneva and 
continue in Pyongyang and Seoul interchangeably. 
  The diplomat said that in the framework of organizing the 
conference it would be useful to hold preliminary unofficial 
consultations of all interested sides in Moscow. "It is 
absolutely unnecessary for everyone to sit at the same table. 
We understand that some participants would find it hard to 
communicate directly therefore we do not rule out the 
possibility of mediators", Panov said. 
  He added that a conference of six countries, representatives 
of the UN Secretary General and the General Director of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency is not the final format and 
the list of participants could be extended. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-17808 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov061_a_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-061 </AU>
