<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   China, ROK `Unanimous' in Ignoring Russian Initiative </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM3003101194 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 30 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM3003101194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Vladimir Skosyrev report: "Beijing and Seoul Ignore </F>
Kozyrev Initiative"] 
  [Text] Beijing -- South Korean President Kim Yong-sam, who 
is ending his trip to China, will be going home empty-handed. 
At least as regards the DPRK's nuclear program, nothing came of 
the Sino-South Korean talks. 
  All Kim Yong-sam's attempts to persuade PRC President Jiang 
Zemin and the other Chinese leaders to exert pressure on 
Pyongyang came to nothing. 
  In response President Jiang reiterated the previous Chinese 
formula, which states that there is no point in transferring the 
issue of inspections of all North Korean nuclear installations 
to the UN Security Council, much less in taking sanctions 
against Pyongyang. 
  Moreover, referring to the U.S. intention to site Patriot 
missiles in the southern part of the peninsula and to resume the 
"Team Spirit" military maneuvers, the PRC leader said that such 
measures could only exacerbate tension still further. Jiang 
took the same tone on this issue as the DPRK Foreign Ministry, 
which has described the reinforcement of U.S. and South Korean 
forces as a step toward war. 
  While they found no common ground on the key subject of 
finding a way to resolve the present crisis, Beijing and Seoul 
were unanimous in ignoring Russia's proposal to convene an 
international conference on removing nuclear weapons from the 
peninsula. Neither side even mentioned the suggestion in their 
exchange of opinions. 
  The PRC president considered it necessary to stress that the 
nuclear problem should be resolved not at a conference but 
within the framework of quadrilateral talks between North and 
South Korea, the United States, and the International Atomic 
Energy Agency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

