<DOCNO> FBIS3-17809 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov061_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Rejects Russian Debt Repayment Terms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003083294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0745 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko] </F>
  [Text] Seoul March 30 TASS -- South Korea has refused to 
accept the terms for a deferment of the repayment of Russia's 
debts on credits which the Seoul government had promised and 
partially provided for the former Soviet Union. Such is the 
outcome of Russian-South Korean talks which ended here on 
Wednesday. 
  At the same time, Mikhail Fradkov, Russian first deputy 
minister for foreign economic relations, who leads the Russian 
delegation at the talks, told ITAR-TASS that "the normal 
negotiating process is underway, and the negotiations will be 
continued". 
  Upon signing an agreement with the "Paris Club" of creditor 
countries in April last year on a rescheduling of the repayment 
of debts to the club member-states, Russia found itself in a 
situation in which it cannot settle with individual creditor 
countries, even non-members of club, including the Republic of 
Korea, on terms that would differ from those set by the Paris 
Club. 
  The Russian side tried to convince the Seoul government of 
the need to accept a debt repayment schedule comparable with the 
Paris Club terms but South Korean financial agencies have not 
agreed to that so far. 
  South Korea provided the Soviet Union with credits amounting 
to 1,470 million U.S. dollars of the promised 3,000 million 
dollars. Russia upon having confirmed the assumption of the 
former Soviet Union's international obligations, paid interest 
in cash and partially through the deliveries of aluminium ingots. 
  However, following the Paris Club's debt rescheduling 
decision, the repayment of Russia's debts to South Korea was 
suspended. The amount of overdue payments as of the end of 
February was about 449 million U.S. dollars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

