<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Supports Proposal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003112494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1042 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003112494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASs -- Russian Federation Council 
speaker Vladimir Shumeyko, during a meeting with journalists, 
supported the proposal made by Kazakhstan President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev to establish a Euro-Asian union. Shumeyko considers 
it possible to establish such a union on a new basis, not just 
recreate the former Soviet Union. 
  Shumeyko's opinion is that it is possible to create a new 
union on the basis of the already existing CIS institutions: 
The Council of the Heads of State, the Council of the Heads of 
Government, and the Interparliamentary Assembly. 
  He also believes that it is essential gradually to establish 
"supranational institutions which would administer such a 
union." One can speak about the creation of common armed forces, 
a common monetary system and that there is no need for borders, 
Shumeyko remarked, being of the opinion that it is time to moot 
these ideas in society. 
  Speaking about his recent visit to France, the Federation 
Council speaker pointed out that he had been particularly 
gratified by the trip to Strasbourg and the decision on Russia's 
accession to the Council of Europe. 
  Shumeyko announced that a peace-making group of the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly, led by Kyrgyzstan parliament chief 
Medetkan Sherimkulov, leaves Moscow for the Transcaucasus on 
Thursday. The delegation will include representatives from a 
number of CIS countries and the Russian Federation Council 
committees. 

</TEXT>

