<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Views Crimean Elections, Poll </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903145194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1348 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903145194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol 29 Mar, TASS -- Last Sunday, the Crimeans 
were taking part not only in the Ukrainian and their own 
parliamentary elections, but also in an opinion poll on some 
important political issues of the peninsula. 
  It is necessary to point out that on the eve of the 
elections 
some political parties and movements called on the Crimeans to 
stay away from the Ukrainian parliamentary elections or, to be 
more exact, not to drop the ballots into the ballot-boxes, but 
take them away. 
  It is not known yet whether the voters paid their attention 
to this call or not, but it was already stated that the Crimean 
parliamentary elections are recognized valid because more than 
60 percent of the electorate took part in the elections (the 
needed number is 50 percent). 
  In accordance with the preliminary data, the "Russia" 
election bloc, which nominated Yuriy Meshkov for the presidency, 
and representatives of the Communist Party are in the lead. 
  The opinion poll, which was conducted on the initiative of 
President Meshkov, known for his pro-Russian sentiments, 
consisted of three questions: Should the Crimea establish its 
relations with Ukraine on the basis of agreements, whether the 
people support the idea of the dual citizenship and whether they 
agree to attach force of law to some decrees by the Crimean 
president. 
  The poll's idea caused a negative reaction in Kiev and the 
Crimean Central Electoral Commission did not participate in its 
organizing. The poll, which is considered a sociological study, 
was conducted by the presidential structures of the peninsula. 
  A group of international observers at the Ukrainian and 
Crimean parliamentary elections held a press-conference on 
Monday. "We did not register any violations of the Crimean 
election legislation or the international election law," Sergey 
Stankevich, Russia's State Duma deputy, told journalists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

