<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Issues Policy Statement on Korean `Crisis' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2903191194 Tallinn ETA in English 1646 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2903191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn ETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["News Release"] </F>
  [Text] Tallinn, March 29 -- The Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs of the Republic of Estonia informed ETA, on Tuesday [29 
March], of its position regarding the continuing refusal of 
North Korea to allow International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
experts adequately to inspect its nuclear sites. 
  The Ministry, in its statement, supports all peaceful 
initiatives to solve the problems on the Korean peninsula and 
considers the solution of the North Korean nuclear inspection 
question to be an important step toward the unification of the 
Korean people. 
  The Ministry supports the international demand as stated in 
United Nations Security Council Resolution 825 (1993) according 
to which North Korea must allow international experts access to 
all its nuclear sites. 
  The Ministry shares the concerns expressed in the IAEA 
resolution of March 21, 1994 about North Korean violations on 
March 13 and 14 of the agreement which had been reached on 
February 15, 1994. 
  The Ministry finds North Korea's behavior in connection with 
the inspection of its nuclear sites to be non-constructive and 
serving to escalate tensions. 
  The Ministry supports the resolution of the resulting crisis 
via negotiations, including if necessary other nations in that 
region into this process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

