<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Condemns 1990 Soviet Troop `Reprisal' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003132994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1312 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The parliament of Azerbaijan qualified the 
introduction of Soviet troops in Baku on January 20, 1990 as a 
reprisal and a grave and unprecedentedly cruel crime against the 
Azerbaijani people. 
  The parliament resolution, adopted on March 29, says that 
the 
blame for this crime rests entirely with the Soviet authorities, 
led by Mikhail Gorbachev, and on the Azerbaijani leadership of 
that time, above all Abdurakhman Vizirov and Viktor Polyanichko, 
then first and second secretaries of the Azerbaijani Communist 
Party; Ayaz Mutalibov, the chairman of the Cabinet of Ministers, 
Elmira Gafarova, the chairperson of the parliament's presidium, 
and Vagif Gusseynov, the chairman of Azerbaijan's KGB. Legal 
action has been initiated against these figures and also against 
former head of the Azerbaijani KGB's 4th department Nikolay 
Starchenkov, and Mark Shmotkin, the commander of the Baku Higher 
Military School, who organized an explosion in the Azerbaijani 
TV center. 
  The document also says that legal action against Polyanichko 
and Gafarova were stopped because of the said figures' death. 
  Meanwhile, some of the deputies insisted that the list of 
those guilty of the tragedy shall be supplemented with the names 
of Yevgeny Primakov, Dmitriy Yazov, Nikolay Kryuchkov and Vadim 
Bakatin. 
  Most of the deputies agreed with President Gaydar Aliyev, 
who 
said that the blame for the tragedy rests with the former Soviet 
state. 
  A leader of the parliamentary opposition Etibar Mamedov 
believes that the final assessment of the events in Baku in 
January 1990, may only be given by a new parliament, not the 
current one, elected during the rule of communists. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

