<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Informs Parliament on UN Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903211494 Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY in Russian 
1445 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903211494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi CONTACT INFORMATION AGENCY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The latest session of the Georgian parliament was 
held today, 29 March, and was addressed by the head of state, 
Eduard Shevardnadze. In his address, he commented on the 
Security Council's last resolution on the situation in Abkhazia, 
in which, the head of state stressed, "the stance of the 
Republic of Georgia" is confirmed. The head of state said that 
the resolution of the Security Council was a balanced document 
in which the legal status of Abkhazia was defined clearly within 
the framework of single, indivisible Georgia. It allows the 
hope that the question will be resolved by exclusively political 
means. 
  The head of the Georgian state especially singled out the 
formulation of the Security Council's resolution concerning the 
refugees who, according to Paragraph 3 of the resolution, must, 
without any limits, return to their homes in all rayons of 
Abkhazia. 
  Shevardnadze once again confirmed the readiness of the 
Georgian side to negotiate with the representatives of Abkhazia, 
despite the resumption of war by the separatists in the Kodori 
gorge. 
  The chairman of the republic's parliament announced with 
responsibility, before parliament and the state, that Georgia 
had not initiated the current escalation of tension in the 
Abkhazian Svaneti and the rayons adjacent to the Inguri River 
and that Georgia would not betray its course of "peaceful and 
political settlement of the conflict, about which the United 
Nations, the Security Council, and Russia must be informed". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

