<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   First Round of South Ossetia Elections Ends </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903151394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1319 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Preliminary reports show that 702000060100f members of the 
new parliament were elected in the Saturday elections in South 
Ossetia, the self-proclaimed republic within Georgia. This was 
reported to INTERFAX on Tuesday by the South Ossetian leader 
Ludvig Chibirov who pointed to the high turnout. A total of 80 
of registered voters cast their ballots. 
  The second round of voting is scheduled for April 10. 
Chibirov will also run the second time because there are five 
more candidates in his electoral district. 
  Meanwhile, an aide of the leader of Georgia, that does not 
recognize the republic, has described the elections as illegal. 
In an interview Vazha Khachapuridze said they were aimed at the 
separation of South Ossetia from Georgia. He said the step 
contradicts the trilateral Dagomys agreements and could 
aggravate the situation. "International experts will pass their 
verdict on the lawfulness of the elections", the aide said. 

</TEXT>

