<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Discusses Purpose of Meetings With Yeltsin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003092494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0855 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS -- During their regular 
meetings, the leaders of the houses of the Russian Parliament 
and the president "look for approaches to basic decisions which 
are subsequently elaborated," Federation Council Speaker 
Vladimir Shumeyko told journalists at a roundtable meeting here 
on Wednesday. 
  In response to an ITAR-TASS question about his meeting with 
Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday, Shumeyko remarked that such meetings 
are held periodically when the president needs to discuss some 
matters with law-makers. 
  The Federation Council speaker is confident that the houses 
of parliament "should not be used as an instrument of the 
struggle for power." There is no sense in parliament's 
decision-making "for decision's sake". 
  Decisions made at the state level should be complied with, 
Shumeyko stressed, adding that it is easier to coordinate 
matters at the very first level of the decision making process. 
"Boris Yeltsin did not make any recommendations to the 
Federation Council," Shumeyko specified. 
  Touching upon the notorious coup scenarios, Shumeyko 
described them as an "attempt to undermine the situation in the 
country in order to catch fish in troubled waters." He believes 
that the situation in Russia is now stable enough, and that 
attempts to upset it by such methods look ridiculous and won't 
pan out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-17873 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov061_b_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-061 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Says Yeltsin `Workaholic' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2903151794 Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA in Russian 29 Mar 
94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> PM2903151794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Correspondent Maksim Chikin report under "INFORM" rubric: </F>
"Into Europe by the Front Door"] 
  [Text] Paris -- Last week a Russian parliamentary 
delegation headed by Federation Council Chairman Viktor Shumeyko 
visited France at the Interparliamentary Union's invitation. At 
a press conference devoted to the visit's results the chairman 
reported that he had met with Catherine Lalumiere, secretary 
general of the Council of Europe, in Strasbourg. 
  "Past Russian parliamentarians," Shumeyko said, "have 
insisted that Russia must become a Council member because it is 
so big and great and must therefore have an exception made for 
it. We structured the discussion differently. If Russia meets 
the necessary criteria for admission, we will be glad to be 
accepted into the Council." The Council president replied that 
this question would most probably be decided after the 
parliament's summer recess. 
  Shumeyko said in response to the KOMSOMOLSKAYA PRAVDA 
correspondent's question about Boris Nikolayevich's health that 
certain circles needed a campaign to discredit the president in 
order to destabilize the situation. According to him the 
president is a real "workaholic." He can get up at 0200 and 
work. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

