<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission To Formulate Mechanism for Civil Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003114294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1109 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS -- A special commission is 
being set up to work out a mechanism for implementing the 
agreement on civil accord in Russia. The commission will 
consist of representatives of the Russian president, government, 
both chambers of the parliament, State Duma factions, as well as 
public and cultural figures, according to Federation Council 
speaker Vladimir Shumeyko. 
  The draft agreement says "civil accord should be perceived 
as 
a process to involve all forces of society, which support the 
principles laid in the agreement". Concrete issues are to be 
elaborated at round-table discussions and by ad-hoc work groups, 
the speaker told reporters on Wednesday. 
  Shumeyko stressed that the agreement should be implemented 
only in full compliance with the Russian Constitution and laws. 
The Conciliation Commission will be empowered to examine and 
make public cases of agreement violations by any side, and even 
to demand that the given side be excluded from the signatories. 
  The upper house speaker views the agreement on civil accord 
in Russia as a document of paramount political and social 
importance. But he warned against regarding this document as "a 
substition of the existing Constitution". 
  Shumeyko told reporters that the agreement had been put on 
the agenda of the Federation Council's session scheduled to open 
next week. He called to speed up work on the text, because "if 
we try to bring it to perfection, it may never see the light of 
the day", the speaker emphasised. He believes that the text of 
the draft agreement should be distributed among upper house 
deputies. If they agree to it, they may instruct the Federation 
Council speaker to take part in its filalizing in coordination 
with other structures. A similar procedure should take place in 
the parliament's lower house, as well as in all parties and 
movements, Shumeyko said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

