<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   General Says Charges `Groundless' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903213394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1609 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903213394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deputy head of Russian troops for chemical and 
biological defenses General Valentin Yevstigneyev has described 
as groundless any suspicion about Moscow's violation of the 
international ban on the development, production or storage of 
biological weapons. 
  He was commenting on a Sunday Times publication which 
alleged, referring to intelligence sources and three Russian 
"defectors," that the Russian Defence Ministry was engaged in 
the development of biological weapons behind Yeltsin's back. 
  Yevstigneyev does not consider the paper's report unusual 
given the background of continued Western accusations against 
Russia concerning the developing of such weapons. He said that 
in the past, such campaigns were timed to coincide with major 
international talks on banning biological or chemical weapons in 
an effort to divert attention from the West's own programs which 
were in violation of the 1972 convention. 
  The general said the Sunday Times publication had emerged in 
the run up to a session by a preparatory committee intended to 
clear the ground for a special conference for measures to verify 
the compliance with the 1972 convention. Moscow is expected to 
continue work on possible verification measures at that session, 
Yevstigneyev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

