<H3> <TI>   Karasin: Allegations `Surprising' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903150694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1336 
GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2903150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Aleksandr Krylovich </F>
and Vladimir Taranov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 29 Mar -- Reports in British mass media 
about continued work on the development of biological weapons in 
Russia are to say the least surprising. Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of Foreign Ministry information and press department, 
stated this at today's briefing at the Foreign Ministry press 
center. 
  He said that in September 1992 the governments of three 
countries (Russia, the United States, and the UK) adopted a 
joint statement envisaging a complex of measures to allay the 
parties' concern over abidance by the 1972 convention banning 
biological weapons. As part of the implementation of these 
accords, U.S. and British experts have visited four nonmilitary 
biological facilities in Russia. The experts' conclusions by no 
means correspond with the claims made in the British press, 
Grigoriy Karasin noted. 
  It is regrettable that "information" of this kind is 
appearing at a time when Russia, the United States, and the UK, 
who are the depositories of the convention banning biological 
weapons, are making joint efforts to call a special convention 
on possible verification measures as early as this year, 
Grigoriy Karasin noted. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

