<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Rumors' Seen as Politically Motivated </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903170094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1601 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903170094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 29 TASS -- Biological arms rumors 
initiated by foreign mass media have political coloring, Russian 
academician Valentin Fedorov told ITAR-TASS here today. 
  According to the academician, recent open hearings at the 
State Duma on chemical disarmament excluded a possibility of 
speculations on this issue. He said that specialists disclosed 
all secrets of the "classified arms". 
  A refutation was also published by the Russian Defence 
Ministry, which clearly said that Russia does not develop or 
produce biological arms. 
  Academician Fedorov and other experts wonder why 
"sensations" 
casting aspersions on the Russian reputation appear at a time of 
Russian stabilization. Ecological problems are most often used 
in these "exposures". Rumors claiming alleged Russian holding 
of ecologically-dangerous weapons were spread under the pretext 
of environmental protection. According to well-informed 
sources, another attack to use consequences of Russian nuclear 
programs is being prepared. 
  In the opinion of specialists, chemical disarmament problems 
are concentrated around technologies for elimination of combat 
poison gases. They have an economic competition basis, and 
biological arms problems have a clear political coloring. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

