<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Industry Ready To Cooperate With Old Partners </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003133994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1109 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003133994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The head of the Russian state-owned Rosvooruzheniye 
company Victor Samoylov believes that this year the country can 
sell armaments and military hardware worth $20 Bn. Last year 
the figure was around $2 Bn. 
  In a Tuesday interview with Interfax Samoylov said that 
Russia did not lose the arms markets of the former Soviet Union 
and is ready to expand cooperation in this sphere with 
traditional partners: Arab countries, India, China, African and 
East European nations. 
  According to Samoylov, the volume of sales has been falling 
due to the form of payments. Since 1991 Russia has been 
demanding immediate payment and has stopped giving credits to 
countries for importing its armaments. 
  He said that last year the U.S. sold approximately the same 
amount of weapons at the same terms as Russia. "The $30 Bn 
volume of trade the Americans speak of is credited," he said. 
  Samoylov added that the USSR offered credits for 7 to 40 
years for the purchase of its weaponry. He also said that 
Russia lost between 10 and 15 billion dollars because of UN 
sanctions against its old partners: Libya and Iraq. He said 
Western states received compensation from the United Nations and 
the IMF for breaking off economic ties with the two countries. 
According to the head of Rosvooruzhenie, only Russia was left 
without compensation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

