<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Argues More Funds Needed for Military Hardware </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903121394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1030 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903121394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian First Deputy Defense Minister Andrey 
Kokoshin told Interfax that the country's military doctrine made 
no sense unless cash was made available to buy military 
hardware. "In order to cut the funds for defense factories, the 
government-approved state defense contracts would have to be 
revised," he said. 
  Kokoshin said that the Defense Ministry needed nearly Rbs 28 
trillion for purchases of military hardware in 1994 while the 
Finance Ministry was prepared to allocate one fifth of that 
amount. 
  He said that the Defense Ministry would press for its needs, 
in particular through the State Duma. He added that the 
ministry "had appropriate instructions on this score from the 
president and the prime minister." 
  Kokoshin listed numerous reasons for the shortage of funds 
in 
his ministry, notably slow restructuring of Russian industry, 
the need for it to maintain a large social role for its 
employees and low demand for the civilian production of 
converted defense factories. He said that defense production 
proper accounted for as little as 20 percent of the defense 
industry's output and there were no customers for the remaining 
80 percent. "For this reason aircraft, ships, locomotives so 
needed by the railroad ministry and tank-trucks are 
stockpiling," he emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

