<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference at State Duma </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903201894 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903201894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by unidentified correspondent on news conference </F>
given by LDPR leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy at the State Duma on 
29 March; Zhirinovskiy's remarks recorded] 
  [Excerpts] [Video shows Zhirinovskiy at news conference] 
  [Zhirinovskiy] I am starting to go sour. I need an enemy, 
somebody to fight with. The Communists and the Democratic 
Russians are lying down -- who can I fight with? I cannot kick 
a man when he is down, understand? There is nobody to fight. 
  [Correspondent] That is how the LDPR [Liberal Democratic 
Party of Russia] leader assessed the political power of his 
party today. [passage omitted] The first task of the LDPR now is 
the struggle for the rights of Russians in the former Soviet 
Union, and, says Zhirinovskiy, this struggle will be merciless. 
  [Zhirinovskiy] We will use all the most effective means to 
defend our population, so that they will always [words 
indistinct] to touch citizens of the Russian state, always. 
There will only be a scorched desert left. There will be 
nothing left. 
  [Correspondent] Apart from that, the leader of the LDPR once 
more made a firm prediction for the geopolitical future of the 
former republics of the Soviet Baltic. 
  [Zhirinovskiy] You will get a governor general of the Baltic 
guberniya, a Russian, in the capital, in Riga, you will get a 
small town of Tallinn choking without light or heat, where 
Estonians will catch fish and eat them cold because there will 
be no electricity, and the town of Kaunas, the capital of the 
little Lithuanian state. You will definitely get that. A weak 
little national banner will flap in the wind over those two 
territories, Kaunas and Tallinn. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

