<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Russia' Bloc `Unquestioned Leader' in Crimean Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2903155194 Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network in 
Ukrainian 1400 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> WS2903155194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Ukrayinske Radio First Program Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The complexity of the elections for the Crimean 
Supreme Soviet which took place on Sunday [27 March] 
considerably slowed down the vote-counting process. [Word 
indistinct] results of the election will probably not be made 
public until Wednesday, the general outcome is known. Our 
correspondent reported that (?so far) 12 deputies to the Crimean 
parliament were elected in single-seat districts. The Russia 
bloc, supported by 77 percent of the electorate, became the 
unquestioned leader in multiseat districts, where the elections 
were based on party preference. (?Most of) the 14 legislative 
seats earmarked for parties were won by this bloc. The 
Communists can count on only one or two seats in the Crimean 
parliament; as little as 11 percent of the electorate voted for 
them. In the Crimean Tatar national electoral districts, most 
of the seats were garnered by candidates proposed by the 
kurultay [congress of all Tatars], who won the support of 89 
percent of the constituency. Representatives of the displaced 
Crimean people are allocated 14 out of a total 98 seats in the 
Crimean Supreme Soviet. 

</TEXT>

