<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimea's Deputy Premier Comments on Election Results </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003090794 Moscow 2x2 Television in Russian 0730 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003090794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow 2x2 Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on the results of the Crimean elections 
and the opinion poll, Yevgeniy Saburov, deputy prime minister of 
the Crimean Government, told POSTFACTUM that the question of 
treaty-based relations between Crimea and Kiev would only ease 
tension, but by no means lead to the breakdown of Ukraine. In 
his words, both the elections and the poll actually recorded the 
existing situation. The deputy prime minister also stressed that 
Crimea had no intention of breaking away from Ukraine if a 
sensible economic policy is implemented and if the work of the 
Crimean leadership is not disrupted. However, it was clear that 
this was unrealistic in the near future, Saburov said. 
  Therefore, Crimea is going to raise the question of special 
relations, first and foremost in the economic sphere, and it 
will go as far as concluding international treaties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

