<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Premier Satisfied With Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903204994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1836 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903204994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Russian economist recently appointed deputy 
prime minister of Ukraine's Autonomous Republic of Crimea 
expressed satisfaction with a meeting he had with Ukrainian 
President Leonid Kravchuk. 
  Yevgeniy Saburov told INTERFAX-Ukraine that the meeting, 
held 
on Tuesday, focused on "general aspects of the relations between 
Ukraine and Crimea." At the same time, "a fairly concrete 
matter was (also) given consideration, the beginning of economic 
reform in Crimea." "Since that matter doesn't contradict the 
law on the sharing of powers between Ukraine and Crimea, there 
couldn't have been much friction," Saburov said. 
  Asked whether the relationship between Ukraine and its 
autonomous republic could be based on a treaty, he said, "this 
would eliminate the problem of (Crimea's) secession (from 
Ukraine)." 
  As for the possibility of using the Russian ruble in Crimea, 
Saburov said, "cash rubles are in circulation in Crimea anyway, 
as they are in Kiev, for that matter." He said the Crimean 
government planned to shortly open ruble bank accounts for the 
autonomous republic's enterprises. "As for the idea that 
Russian Central Bank rubles could be poured into the economy of 
Crimea, who will give them to us?" Saburov said. 
  He said granting him Ukrainian citizenship was "under 
consideration." Saburov, who is a Russian citizen but needs 
Ukrainian citizenship to carry out his duties as deputy premier, 
said he favored dual citizenship for Crimea's population. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

