<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zyuganov Says Elections Show Feelings Turning Left </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003084094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0753 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Reports by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova </F>
and by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] 
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS -- "Another round of local 
elections in Russia confirmed once again that the popular 
feelings are sharply turning left," leader of the Communist 
Party of the Russian federation Gennadiy Zyuganov told ITAR-TASS. 
  In his opinion, the electors voted for "people with socially 
oriented thinking, and the alliance between patriots and 
supporters of a strong state is gaining in strength." Aman 
Tuleyev's victory in Kuzbass, which was "the stronghold of 
radical democrats quite recently", is convincing proof of it, 
Zyuganov believes. In his opinion, the same trend became 
prominent in Ukraine, which follows from the "convincing victory 
of the left-wing forces in eastern Ukraine and a strong support 
for state-oriented forces in the Crimea." Everywhere, with the 
exception of western Ukraine, "the opposition is being 
consolidated. Actually, it is the opposition to shock therapy 
and the breaking of ages-long ties between the three great 
Slavonic nations", Zyuganov continued. 
  Commenting on the situation in the Crimea, he pointed out 
that although the public opinion poll, held there, has no legal 
force, it does reflect people's feelings, and "both Moscow and 
Kiev will have to take it into account." 
  The Russian Communist leader said that the Communist party 
of 
the Russian Federation favoured the closest possible 
rapprochement of Moscow, Kiev and Simferopol, and not their 
drifting apart. "We shall hold a well-considered stand, aimed 
at improving relations between the Crimea, Ukraine and Russia... 
Nobody is encroaching upon anybody else's sovereignty, but 
there can be no real sovereignty, if economic relations are 
disintegrating," Zyuganov said. 
  Moscow March 30 TASS -- Thirty four members of the Communist 
Party of the Russian Federation were elected to representative 
bodies in subjects of the Federation at the local elections last 
Sunday. A total of 216 Communist candidates took part in the 
elections, a spokesman for the department for work with the 
territories at the president's administration told ITAR-TASS. 
  The activity of Communist candidates was rather high, but no 
more than 16 per cent of them won the elections. Thus, only two 
out of 27 Communist candidates got the needed number of votes in 
the Voronezh region, and as many in the Rostov region, where 31 
Communists were standing for election. One out of 20 Communist 
candidates was elected in the Kursk region. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

