<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Faction Contemplates Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3003094894 Tallinn BNS in English 1756 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS3003094894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 29, BNS -- If the Saeima (parliament) 
ratifies the Latvian-Russian troop withdrawal accord, the 
National Independence Movement [LNNK] might consider 
resignation, faction member Aristids Lembergs told reporters 
Tuesday [29 March]. 
  Faction head Alexander Kirsteins, however, questioned the 
option as legally and technically impossible. The parliament 
may be dissolved exclusively by the president, according to the 
country's Constitution, said the faction's deputy head Andrejs 
Krastins. 
  If one of the factions withdrew from the parliament, the 
president may be forced to consider the parliament's 
dissolution, said Krastins. 
  LNNK has not discussed the resignation issue with other 
factions in the parliament's National Bloc yet but Lembergs 
predicted they could approve of the motion. 
  The National Bloc dislikes the Latvian-Russian agreement for 
concession to Russia's demands of the Skrunda radar operation 
and the social guarantees to war pensioners in return for Aug. 
31 as the withdrawal deadline. 
  The National Bloc includes parliament factions of LNNK, 
Homeland and Freedom, Christian Democrats Union. They have been 
pressuring President Guntis Ulmanis and the parliament not to 
sign and ratify the agreement since it was initialed on March 15. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

