<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Endorses Agreements With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003032094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0150 
GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003032094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Riga, 30 Mar -- The Latvian Government has endorsed 
the package of agreements with Russia initialled by the 
delegations of both countries at talks in Moscow on 15 March. 
The cabinet of ministers considers the quick signing and 
ratification in the Saeima of these documents as "the only real 
guarantee of the withdrawal of Russian troops from the Latvian 
territory before 31 August this year," says the government 
statement adopted late evening on 29 March. The document 
stresses that the fixed term of the final troops pullout will 
enhance the possibility of international monitoring of this 
process. It also says that many countries have supported the 
initialled agreements and "have described them as a success of 
Latvian diplomacy." 
  Let us recall that of the four documents that form this 
package, the national forces have mostly criticized two: on 
temporarily maintaining the radio intercepting station in 
Skrunde and on the social protection of military pensioners. 
The government describes the treaty on the radar as a 
compromise and concedes that in the absence of an agreement the 
station would have been working uncontrollably for an indefinite 
period. The cabinet members believe this document will enable 
Latvia's cooperation with Western collective security systems 
and show Latvia's readiness to reach a compromise in the 
interests of the international community. As for military 
pensioners, the statement says their status will be defined by 
Latvian laws, "and the Russian side's claims that they should be 
granted citizenship have been turned down." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

