<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Box Retrieved From Plane Crash Raises Questions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2903192894 Moscow NTV in Russian 1800 GMT 29 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2903192894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As the IZVESTIYA newspapaer said today, initial 
information on the contents of the black boxes from the Russian 
Airbus that crashed in Siberia has been received from Paris. 
The catastrophe on 22 March killed 75 people. 
  [Unidentified correspondent over video of crash site] The 
results of the analysis of the contents of the black boxes are 
to be announced tomorrow. However it is already known today 
that despite earlier interpretations, the crew of the Airbus 
were alive and continuing to converse among themselves in the 
last few minutes of flight. Specialists will, therefore, have 
to refute the theory that the catastrophe came about as a result 
of instantaneous decompression. The Russian experts in Paris 
will attempt to identify the pilots' voices and draw up a 
precise transcript of the conversation. 
  At the same time, the other box, in which the functional 
parameters of all the components of the Airbus are recorded, is 
being decoded. The information retrieval process will probably 
take up until the end of this week, and the results of the 
decoding will be passed to members of the investigative 
commission. Only then will the final verdict be made. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

