<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   }Strikes Threatened in St. Petersburg </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  944F0494B St. Petersburg SANKT PETERBURGSKIYE VEDOMOSTI in 
Russian 23 Mar 94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> 944F0494B </F>
<F P=104>  St. Petersburg SANKT PETERBURGSKIYE VEDOMOSTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by V. Novikov: "Strike Committees Are Politicized"] </F>
  [Text]]While creating strike committees in 
productions included in the Kirovskiy Zavod Association, the 
consolidated Kirovskiy trade union committee suggests creating a 
citywide strike committee as well. In the words of the 
association's trade union leader, Vladimir Yudin, the task of 
the strike committee today is not to organize but, on the 
contrary, to warn about protest actions. 
  The most politically active Kirovskiy Zavod has it no worse 
than other enterprises of the city. The average wages are close 
to 200,000 rubles [R]. Only about 4,000 people have been laid 
off from the tractor and former tank productions, but they 
receive a stipend of 44,000. For steel smelters who have work 
orders, the wages are generally twice the average. Nonetheless, 
the workers, in Yudin's words, are prepared for protest actions, 
and the steel smelters are guaranteeing their support for the 
unemployed tractor builders. The reason, in the opinion of the 
plant trade union committee, is that the labor collectives 
consider the present economic reforms to be a blind alley. 
Taxes and prices raised by monopolists will sooner or later 
destroy the economy completely. 
  The consolidated city strike committee could also put 
pressure on central and regional authorities in order to develop 
a new economic policy. The strike committees of specific 
productions must "apply pressure" on the administrations of the 
enterprises, but not so as to gain any concessions but so that 
the employer too will influence the government on his own 
behalf. In other words--the strike committees are becoming 
politicized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

