<H3> <TI>   Crimean President's Aide: Ukraine Cannot Finance Fleet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003115094 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
0300 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Black Sea Fleet continues to be a bone of 
contention between Ukraine and Russia. Vladimir Bezkorovannyy, 
commander of Ukraine's Naval Forces, believes the naval vessels 
of the coastal service of the Black Sea Fleet must be divided 
equally between Russia and Ukraine. However, in the opinion of 
Valeriy Kuznetsov, adviser to the Crimean president for military 
issues, Ukraine is not capable of financing combat training even 
with the minimum of vessels at its disposal. 
  The Black Sea Fleet numbers more than 100 naval vessels in 
all; of these only five are Ukrainian. At the same time, as 
Valeriy Kuznetsov emphasized, Ukraine has substantially 
increased the number of its ground armed forces on the territory 
of Crimea. Here there are now about 50,000 Ukrainian servicemen 
together with their construction units. 
  Ukraine is probably afraid of the processes that are taking 
place in Crimea, Valeriy Kuznetsov said, because Crimea is 
Russian in spirit. 

</TEXT>

