<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peacekeeping Forces General Says Republic Needs No Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003191494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1823 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The commander of the CIS peacekeeping force in 
Tajikistan said he saw no reasons for Tajikistan to have an army 
of its own. 
  "Large-scale aggression against Tajikistan is out of the 
question, although groups of 50 to 200 men might try to break 
into the territory of the Republic, hoping to get support from 
groups within (Tajikistan) and pursuing political aims," 
Colonel-General Boris Pyankov told reporters in Dushanbe on 
Wednesday. He said he was sure the 15 April deadline for the 
peacekeepers' presence in Tajikistan would be moved to 31 
December. 
  Pyankov said all financial and other problems the 
Commonwealth force initially faced had been solved. He said 
Russia was paying 50 percent of the expenditure for the 
peacekeepers, Uzbekistan and Kazakhstan were paying 15 percent 
each, and Tajikistan and Kyrgyzstan 10 percent each. 
  The general said Tajikistan's leadership wished the force to 
be enlarged and that it might suggest that Armenia, Ukraine and 
Belarus send in reinforcements. But he doubted that Belarus 
would send in any troops, its legislation banning the use of its 
armed forces outside its territory. 
  Pyankov on the whole expressed approval of the idea of 
having 
more CIS states involved in the peacekeeping mission, for this 
would "eliminate all mistrust and give the lie to the 
accusations that Russia acts as an imperial power." 
  He said the initiative for giving the peacekeepers the 
status 
of a U.N. force had nearly been killed off, the United Nations 
being unable to fund it. But Russia is ready to pay for its 
peacekeepers anywhere in the CIS if the United Nations 
recognizes those expenses as Russia's payments for U.N. 
peacekeeping missions, Pyankov said. He said a proposal to that 
effect might be made to U.N. secretary General Butrus 
Butrus-Ghali, currently visiting Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-17953 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov062_m_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-062 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Agreement Signed With Russia on Military Call Up </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003134794 Dushanbe Radio Tajikistan Network in Tajik 1200 
GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003134794 </F>
