<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIS Assembly Delegation To Tour Transcaucasus </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003183194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1746 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow March 30 TASS -- A delegation of the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly will set off tomorrow on a tour of 
Transcaucasian republics in search for ways of settling the 
Armenian-Azerbaijani conflict over the Nagorno-Karabakh enclave. 
  The delegation, headed by Kyrgyz parliament chairman 
Medetkan 
Sherimkulov, is made up of representatives of Russia, Kyrgyzia 
and Belarus. The CIS parliamentarians are scheduled to visit 
Baku, Yerevan and Stepanakert, and meet Azerbaijani, Armenian 
and Nagorno-Karabakh leaders. 
  The previous tour by CIS lawmakers of the Transcaucasia with 
a peacekeeping mission was taken last September. The 
parliamentarians met for three times with Azerbaijani President 
Geydar Aliyev, discussed the possibilities of resolving the 
crisis with Armanian President Levon Ter-Petrosyan and the 
Nagorno-Karabakh leadership. The delegation also visited 
Azerbaijan's border regions and makeshift camps of refugees in 
the Belyagan and Barda districts, met heads of district 
administrations. The tour resulted in an agreement between the 
CIS parliamentary delegation and the Karabakh leaders about a 
month-long ceasefire and partial return of refugees to their 
homes. According to the lawmakers, to finally settle the 
Karabakh conflict, the warring sides will need time, patience 
and negotiating skills. 
  A new impetus was imparted to CIS parliamentarians' 
peacekeeping efforts by the Moscow meeting of Armenian and 
Azerbaijani defence ministers with the participation of a 
Nagorno-Karabakh representative. The meeting was held in 
February at the initiative of the Russian defence minister and 
resulted in an agreement on a complete ceasefire and gradual 
settlement of the conflict. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev met on Wednesday 
with 
Sherimkulov to discuss the forthcoming trip by the CIS 
Interparliamentary Assembly mission to Nagorno-Karabakh. 
  After the meeting, the Kyrgyz parliament speaker told TASS 
that at the moment the interparliamentary peacekeeping group was 
arranging a meeting of Armenian, Azerbaijani and Karabakh 
lawmakers in the Kyrgyz capital of Bishkek. 
  "We would like to hope that our activities will help restore 
peace. People are tired of war, of increasing numbers of 
refugees. None of the states will profit by this", Sherimkulov 
stressed. "if we manage to promote rapprochement between the 
warring sides, we would consider our mission helpful", he said. 
  A senior official of the Russian Foreign Ministry told 
reporters that the ministry fully supported the intention of the 
CIS Interparliamentary Assembly's peacekeeping group to promote 
the Nagorno-Karabakh settlement. According to him, the Russian 
Foreign Ministry "is working in close coordination (with the 
group) and is ready to render an expert assistance in the 
activities conducted by the group". Russian diplomats beleive 
this group "may play a special role, since parliamentarians can 
help create a favourable atmosphere for concluding an agreement, 
which is presently being drafted by executive structures". 
  According to the Foreign Ministry high-ranking official, the 
main thing to do now is "to bring the sides together, to create 
a proper atmosphere for signing an agreement to halt the 
conflict in Nagorno-Karabakh". The agreement has already being 
worked out in principle. Each of the conflicting sides has its 
own approaches, therefore it will certainly take much effort to 
have the agreement signed, the diplomat stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

