<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communist Party Nominates Novikaw </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3003134894 Minsk SEM DNEY in Russian 26 Mar 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> WS3003134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk SEM DNEY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Ivan Vasilevich: "Presidential Marathon Has </F>
Begun"] 
  [Text] The Belarusian Party of Communists [PKB], which 
until recently opposed the introduction of a presidency in the 
Republic, will participate in the presidential elections. This 
decision was adopted at the plenum of the Central Committee 
convened to discuss the new political situation, which developed 
after the Supreme Soviet passed a corresponding law. PKB 
members nominated Vasil Novikaw, secretary of the PKB Central 
Committee, as their candidate for president. 
  Assessing this fact, numerous experts and observers notice 
that the left and left-centrist forces composing the People's 
Movement of Belarus, have probably not agreed on a single 
candidate for the job of Belarus' first president. At the same 
time, the opposite wing presents only one candidate for this 
post -- Stanislav Shushkevich. He was proposed by the Belarusian 
Social Democratic Assembly. The Belarusian Union of 
Entrepreneurs did not remain aloof and proposed its president, 
Vladimir Karyagin, to participate in the presidential race. 
However, in the immediate future, everything could change and 
it is not ruled out that we will learn about other -- left, 
right, centrist, independent, and, by all means, unexpected -- 
candidates. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

