<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Positive Result in Plebiscite on Crimea-Ukraine Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3103111694 Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service in Ukrainian 
1000 GMT 31 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3103111694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev Radio Ukraine World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, in Simferopol, Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov is to hold a news conference for journalists on the 
results of the plebiscite. Its results were determined last 
night. The first question was: Are you in favor of renewing the 
provision in the Constitution of the Republic of Crimea dated 6 
May 1992, which defines the regulation of relations between the 
Republic of Crimea and Ukraine on the basis of agreements and 
treaties? This question was answered in the affirmative by 78.4 
percent of the people. Dual citizenship was backed by 82.8 
percent of those polled. Around 80 percent of Crimea's 
population believe that the Crimean president's directives on 
the issues, that are temporarily not settled by the Republic of 
Crimea's legislation, should be granted the status of laws. 
  Over 1 million Crimeans took part in the plebiscite. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

