<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Keeping Conscripts Within Crimea </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003134894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1234 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD3003134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Yefim Shvartsman] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol 30 Mar, TASS -- The Crimean authorities 
"have no intention of whipping up confrontation" caused by 
Kiev's negative reaction to Crimean President Yuriy Meshkov's 
decision banning recruiting offices to send conscripts outside 
the Crimea this spring, a presidential aide said. 
  Valeriy Kuznetsov, Meshkov's military adviser, told 
ITAR-TASS 
on Wednesday that consultations are now underway with a top 
military commander from the Odessa military district to iron out 
disagreements and work out a compromise. 
  The most probable solution would be to leave half of 3,400 
draftees in the Crimea and send 20 per cent (about 680 people) 
to the Ukrainian Army and 1,000 (about 30 per cent) to the Black 
Sea Fleet, he said. 
  Kuznetsov said the other half will be sent to adjacent 
Ukrainian regions for military training since the Crimea does 
not have enough training facilities and expressed the hope that 
30 to 40 per cent of them will return to the Republic upon the 
completion of studying. 
  Speaking about the autumn drafting campaign, Kuznetsov said 
that "we hope all prerequisites and conditions will be created 
for military service in the Crimea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

