<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Aide Rejects Claim to Half of Coastal Fleet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM3003142794 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
0300 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PM3003142794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast: Video report from Sevastopol by </F>
Ye. Orobtsova and A. Lomakin] 
  [Text] [Orobtsova] The Black Sea Fleet remains a bone of 
contention between Ukraine and Russia. Vladimir Bezkorovannyy, 
commander of the Ukrainian Naval Forces, believes that the naval 
vessels of the Black Sea Fleet's coastal service should be 
divided equally between Russia and Ukraine. However, in the 
opinion of Valeriy Kuznetsov, the Crimean president's military 
adviser, Ukraine is not capable of financing combat training 
even with the minimal number of ships at its disposal. The 
Black Sea Fleet numbers more than 100 naval vessels in all, only 
five of which are Ukrainian. Meanwhile, as Valeriy Kuznetsov 
stressed, Ukraine has considerably increased the number of its 
ground forces on Crimean territory, where there are now around 
50,000 Ukrainain servicemen together with their construction 
units. Ukraine is probably afraid of the processes that are 
taking place in Crimea, Valeriy Kuznetsov said, because Crimea 
is Russian in spirit. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

