<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views Russian-Kazakhstan Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM3003162594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 31 Mar 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM3003162594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleksandr Krasulin: "Nursultan Nazarbayev: We </F>
Shall Be Together"] 
  [Text] "Having signed the package of Kazakhstan-Russian 
documents on Monday we laid a foundation for our two states to 
enter the 21st century together. And that accords with our 
peoples' aspirations," stated Kazakhstan President Nursultan 
Nazarbayev at a meeting with Moscow Mayor Yuriy Luzhkov in which 
representatives of business circles and the intelligentsia took 
part. 
  This meeting was a kind of summing up of the results of the 
Kazakhstan leader's first official visit to Russia. Nursultan 
Nazarbayev shared with those present his thoughts about the 
situation in Kazakhstan and Russia and the prospects for the 
development of bilateral relations. In particular he noted that 
he does not agree with the model of the reforms which have been 
implemented in Russia. Privatization from below has not 
succeeded and "has merely led to chaos" so Kazakhstan has 
decided to create state holding companies. In agriculture they 
have rejected the privatization of land and allowed its leasing 
for a period of 99 years with the right of inheritance. 
Kazakhstan has taken the path of retaining strong collective 
and state farms but on new terms. Here those who want to can 
always leave and start their own business when they have 
received their share. 
  The president dwelled in detail on the nationalities 
problem. 
He said that it has arisen as a result of the collapse of "one 
state in which we all lived." Then Kazakhstan "was pushed out 
of the ruble zone" and that merely created additional 
difficulties for people. "If there was the certainty that dual 
citizenship would make it possible to resolve the problem, we 
would introduce it. But in this case the problem would still 
remain at the daily routine level." 
  Nursultan Nazarbayev stated that as president of a sovereign 
state he cannot accept the formation that is the CIS. Of the 
270 documents adopted by the CIS one of its members has approved 
40, another 140, another 150. By creating independent states 
all former republics of the USSR hoped that they would sell 
their goods to Europe and receive dollars in exchange. But it 
has turned out that we had a common market and our goods were 
only necessary to us. "The time has come for a tougher 
association," he said. A Eurasian Union based on principles 
completely distinct from the present community could be such an 
association, the president said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

