<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ulmanis Briefs Bildt on Agreements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003195494 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 1700 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Latvian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Swedish Prime Minister Carl Bildt came to Latvia 
today for a brief working visit. The guest had a meeting with 
President Guntis Ulmanis and also with representatives of the 
Foreign Affairs Commission of the Saeima and its head, 
Aleksandrs Kirsteins. 
  The Swedish prime minister emphasized that, in his opinion, 
the initialled agreements with Russia should be signed, because 
such a process of dealing with relations between neighboring 
states is strengthening Latvian ties with Western countries. 
The stability of Latvia is also important to the Nordic 
countries. Also, the United States has become morally involved 
in the forming of the agreements. This process has been 
internationalized, and with internationalization the process is 
significant to the entire Western world. 
  The Swedish prime minister assessed positively the intention 
of Guntis Ulmanis to meet prominent European politicians in the 
nearest future. Quite probably official guarantees would not be 
given during these meetings, Bildt said. The talks, however, 
would assist foreigners in understanding better the difficulties 
connected with the signing of these agreements. 
  Ulmanis told the Swedish prime minister that the inhabitants 
of Latvia have diverse attitudes toward the initialled 
agreements between Latvia and Russia. There is also opposition 
to the government's and the Saeima majority faction's 
standpoint. In the latest sociological poll, 52 percent of the 
participants have expressed themselves against the Skrunda radar 
station remaining in Latvia. The president, too, is receiving 
many letters from writers who are against the initialled 
agreements. 
  The inhabitants are alarmed, most of all, over the social 
guarantees to former Soviet army officers that are envisaged in 
the agreement, because these will allow approximately 100,000 
officers and their families to remain in Latvia. There is also 
no conviction that Russia will fulfill these agreements. The 
president emphasized that it is also not clear what kind of 
guarantees the Western countries could give to Latvia. It also 
cannot be forgotten that Latvia was occupied in 1940, which 
Russia should, after all, recognize. 
  Aleksandrs Kirsteins, head of the Foreign Affairs Commission 
of the Saeima, in turn explained to the guest that the position 
of the State of Latvia on the question of signing the agreement 
must be coordinated with Estonia, because she does not initial 
agreements with Russia in the sphere of social guarantees to 
military pensioners. The prime ministers of Latvia and Estonia 
will meet on 7 April to discuss these questions. The talks are 
envisaged in Rujiena, and the press center of the Cabinet of 
Ministers organizes representatives of the press who would like 
to accompany those travelling there. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-18009 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov062_u_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-062 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  30 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bildt on Latvia's Problems </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD3003200794 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 1545 GMT 30 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3003200794 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Premier Carl Bildt was today on a brief visit to 
Riga, the capital of Latvia, and his aim was to try to speed up 
the agreement on the Russian withdrawal of troops from Latvia. 
[passage omitted] 
  [Correspondent] The agreement exists on paper, but the 
Latvian Government has not taken a final decision on it and 
there is strong opposition in the parliament to some of the 
points in the agreement. One stumbling block has been the 
Russian radar base in Skrunda in west Latvia, but that is 
allowed to remain during a dismantling period of approximately 
five years. Bildt said that Sweden can think of economically 
assisting the dismantling. [passage omitted on Latvia's problem 
with retired Russian military personnel] 
  During his visit to Riga, Bildt held meetings with President 
Guntis Ulmanis and Premier Valdis Birkavs and representatives of 
the opposition. Russia is not treating its former obedient 
Latvia with enough respect. The Latvians for their part must 
understand that Latvians have most to gain from an agreement 
with the Russians -- that was Bildt's message. This is what 
Bildt said on what was discussed in Riga today:. 
  [begin Bildt recording] We have discussed the continuing 
process and this means both the process toward Russia -- where a 
meeting between President Ulmanis and President Yeltsin is 
currently being prepared, where certain outstanding questions 
will be solved -- and the process which must continue when we 
are creating increased understanding both in Latvia and in 
western countries for the Latvian security situation and 
concerns. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

