<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Homeland, Freedom Deputies Demand Information </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS3003195194 Tallinn BNS in English 1843 GMT 30 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS3003195194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Mar 30, BNS -- The Saeima (parliament) 
Homeland and Freedom faction and several Latvian National 
Independence Movement deputies handed Wednesday [30 March] a 
declaration to Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs. 
  In the declaration the deputies demand to be informed about 
the control over the course of Russian army withdrawal, and 
measures which will be taken to prevent the growth of number of 
demobilized officers in Latvia, the Homeland and Freedom faction 
head, Maris Grinblats told reporters. 
  The deputies also demand that the Latvian delegation did not 
initial the agreement between Russian and Latvian governments on 
Russian military pensioners, living in Latvia, and their 
families' social guarantees. 
  Grinblats says that, in accordance with the Defense 
Ministry's given information, the leadership of the Russian 
Northwest Army Group tries to increase the number of retired 
militaries in Latvia. There can be observed a large scale 
demobilization of Russian officers in Latvia, and permissions 
for a stay in Latvia are asked also for the military personnel 
which has already moved to Russia. 
  The deputies consider that the Cabinet has not taken the 
necessary measures to prevent the demobilization of Russian 
militaries in Latvia and transmigration of Russian army in the 
territory of Latvia. They claim that the Cabinet has to prevent 
by way of legislation Russian militaries' involving in the 
activities of business structures, and it has to tightened 
control over procedure of issuing the stay permissions. 

</TEXT>

