<H3> <TI>   Belgian UN Troops Leaving Croatia for Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2802123394 Brussels BELGA in Dutch 1343 GMT 27 Feb 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2802123394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels BELGA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article signed RKX: "Belgian UN Troops Have Left for </F>
Bosnia"; as released by Brussels BELGA Database] 
  [Text] Brussels, 27 Feb (BELGA) -- One company of about 150 
Belgian UN troops left the Baranja region in eastern Croatia on 
Sunday morning [27 February], heading for Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
The Belgian UN troops, who are taking about 15 armored vehicles 
with them, are expected to arrive in Central Bosnia next 
Tuesday, Belgian military sources revealed on Sunday. 
  The decision to send Belgian troops to Bosnia follows a call 
for more troops from British General Michael Rose, the commander 
of the UN troops in Bosnia, who had requested reinforcements 
following the conclusion of a peace agreement between the 
Muslims and Croats there. 
  No final decision has yet been made on where the Belgian 
troops will be stationed. The front between Muslim and Croatian 
troops is 350 km long. An advance party of Belgian soldiers 
already left the Baranja region on Saturday, and is due to 
arrive Monday in Bosnian Santici in order to reconnoiter. 
Shortly afterwards a decision will be made as to where the 
Belgian troops will be stationed. 

</TEXT>

