<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fabbri: NATO Essential To Counter Russian Threat </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2802125094 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1615 GMT 25 
Feb 93 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2802125094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Fabbri on the `Russian Problem,' </F>
Italian Adherence"] 
  [Text] Rome, 25 Feb (ANSA) -- For Italian Defense Minister 
Fabio Fabbri, "the West once again faces the Russian problem" 
created by the void left after the dissolution of the Warsaw 
Pact. 
  "Either the West fills that void, or Russia will return to a 
position of dominance," said Fabbri, speaking at the sidelines 
of a ceremony to inaugurate the 84th course of the NATO Defense 
College at which he participated today along with President of 
the Republic Oscar Luigi Scalfaro. 
  "The active role of NATO thus remains very important," the 
minister said, adding he concurred with the view of German 
Military Chief of Staff Klaus Naumann, who expressed with 
"crystal clarity" said Fabbri, what was usually said only 
cautiously in the political-diplomatic sphere: "The unpleasant 
truth that the West now has to face the Russian problem." 
  While that country was "politically and economically weak, 
it 
remains strong in conventional and atomic weapons," he added. 
"Perhaps as a result of this weakness," Russia now wants "a new 
Yalta conference and the right to a free hand over what it 
considers its untouchable sphere of influence," he said. 
  In other comments, Fabbri called Communist Refoundation's 
position on NATO "out of tune and frankly surprising." That 
left-wing party's secretary Fausto Bertinotti has declared that 
NATO was out of date and no longer needed. 
  "Never before as in this moment has the Atlantic alliance 
been so timely," said Fabbri "precisely because the cold war is 
over and it is necessary to seek a new equilibrium." NATO is 
"essential for Western security and for international order," he 
said. 
  (In other related news, it was announced that the secretary 
of Italy's Left Democrats would visit NATO headquarters in 
Brussels Monday [28 February], where he would meet Secretary 
General Manfred Woerner just before noon before attending a 
lunch with top members of the Alliance's military and political 
staff. 
  Occhetto's visit will be the first by a Left Democrat or 
former Italian Communist to the Allied command. 

</TEXT>

