<H3> <TI>   Russian Economics Minister Confident About G-7 Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2602174794 Hamburg DPA in German 1524 GMT 26 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2602174794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kronberg -- Russian Economics Minister Aleksandr 
Shokhin has expressed confidence concerning the upcoming talks 
with the finance ministers and heads of central banks of the 
seven major industrialized nations. After arriving in Kronberg 
this afternoon for the G-7 meeting, Shokhin stated: "We want to 
take this opportunity to improve our relations with the 
international financial organizations." 
  His delegation will first brief the G-7 representatives on 
the economic and political changes in Russia. Russia's goal is 
closer cooperation with the G-7 and the IMF. With its Bosnia 
initiative, Russia showed a few days ago that it continues to be 
a major power, Shokin pointed out. Russia must improve its 
cooperation with the West, both in political and in economic 
areas. Thus, the economics minister considers that expanding 
the G-7 -- which now consists of the United States, Japan, Great 
Britain, France, Italy, Germany, and Canada -- to include Russia 
is desirable for political and economic reasons. 

</TEXT>

