<F P=101> United Kingdom </F>
<H3> <TI>   CBI Predicts `Modest Growth' for British Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2502133894 London FINANCIAL TIMES in English 24 Feb 94 p 
13 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PM2502133894 </F>
<F P=104>  London FINANCIAL TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Emma Tucker report: "CBI Forecast Trims Hopes for Economy"] </F>
  [Text] Manufacturers saw the best improvement in order 
books for four years in February, but have lowered their 
expectations for economic expansion. 
  The Confederation of British Industry [CBI] yesterday joined 
most other economic forecasters in predicting that the economy 
was poised for only modest growth -- 2.3 per cent this year and 
2.4 per cent next year. 
  The CBI said the downward revisions from last November's 
forecasts -- 2.4 per cent and 2.8 per cent respectively 
reflected the expected impact of tax rises and cuts in public 
spending in the next two years. 
  Meanwhile, its latest industrial trends survey showed that 
the net proportion of companies assessing order books as below 
normal is the least negative since September 1989. Some 19 per 
cent reported their books to be above normal, while 30 per cent 
said they were below. The negative balance of 11 per cent 
compares favourably with negative balances of 21 per cent and 36 
per cent in January and February last year. 
  Export order books are also significantly better than they 
were a year ago, although there has been no improvement since 
December, suggesting a rise in home demand. 
  The survey, carried out between January 24 and February 16, 
covered 1,360 of the UK's biggest manufacturers, which account 
for about half of manufactured exports. 
  It shows that slightly more companies expect to increase 
domestic prices in the next four months than to reduce them. 
The CBI expects inflation to reach 3.1 per cent by the end of 
this year and 3.7 per cent by the end of next year. The 
underlying measure which excludes mortgage interest payments -- 
will stay within the governments 1 per cent to 4 per cent target 
range, but nearer to the top end. 
  Mr Sudhir Junankar, the CBI's associate director, said: 
"Last November's Budget introduced a more restrictive stance on 
personal taxation than we had previously anticipated. This has 
contributed to our downward revision of growth in national 
output." 
  He added that the tax changes had altered the composition of 
economic growth. Consumer spending was now expected to rise 
moderately this year and next, but this would depend on 
individuals running down their savings to offset the slow growth 
in take-home pay. 
  The CBI expects the balance of payments to stay flat this 
year at about 9.7bn pounds -- compared with 9.5bn pounds last 
year -- as recovery in continental Europe leads to a rise in 
exports. Unemployment will fall only slowly. 
  It stressed that a big risk to the forecasts was uncertainty 
about the way in which the economy was likely to respond to the 
spring tax rises. Although the forecast assumes that consumer 
spending will continue to rise, the CBI pointed out that 
consumers could turn out to be more cautious than expected. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

