<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   FRG Soldiers End Beledweyne Mission, Depart </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2802101894 Hamburg DPA in German 0859 GMT 28 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2802101894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- The Bundeswehr has ended its 
humanitarian mission in the Somalian city of Beledweyne. As the 
3d Corps, which is responsible for the Somalia units, stated in 
Koblenz on Monday [28 February], the last FRG soldier left the 
East African city. There is no more material from the German 
Armed Forces in the desert city and the tent city has been 
completely dismantled. 
  The Bundeswehr mission started last May. In August, 1,700 
German soldiers were operational. The main task for the 
Germans, to provide logistical supply for an Indian brigade, 
could never be fulfilled because the Indians were not stationed 
in the Beledweyne area. Hence, the Bundeswehr contingent 
concentrated on humanitarian aid for the population of 
Beledweyne and the neighborhood. The troops built schools and 
dams and dug wells. 
  A spokesman for the 3d Corps added that the last convoy is 
on 
its way to the Somali capital Mogadishu, some 370 km from 
Beledweyne. There have been no incidents. In Mogadishu, the 
soldiers are accommodated in a provisional camp. From there 
they are shipped by German Navy ships to the Kenyan city of 
Mombasa. Some of them will return to Germany from Mombasa as 
early as this Tuesday. The return of the last 250 Bundeswehr 
soldiers is scheduled for 23 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

