<H3> <TI>   Brazil Supports German Seat on Security Council </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402191694 Hamburg DPA in German 1544 GMT 24 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2402191694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn -- Brazil will support Germany's application 
for a nonpermanent two-year seat on the UN Security Council in 
1995/1996. Brazil Foreign Minister Celso Amorim declared 
Brazilian support during a lengthy exchange of views with 
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel (Free Democratic Party of Germany) 
today. In the long run, Germany aspires to a permanent seat on 
the Security Council. The talks that Amorim began at the 
Bundestag this morning focused on economic, technological, and 
environmental cooperation, the Foreign Ministry announced. 
  Both ministers stressed the "excellent state of 
German-Brazilian relations." Kinkel thanked Amorim for his 
support concerning the final control regulation for the 
Brazilian nuclear power plants. He encouraged Brazil to "push 
ahead vigorously" with the ratification of the Tlatelolco 
Treaty, which provides for nuclear-free zones in Latin America 
and the Caribbean. It will "facilitate and widen" technical 
cooperation in the future, Kinkel stressed. 

</TEXT>

