<H3> <TI>   Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister Holds Consultations </TI></H3>
<H4>   Agrees To Debt Rescheduling </H4>
<F P=102> AU2602184794 Hamburg DPA in German 1420 GMT 26 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2602184794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tehran -- Talks on a rescheduling scheme for 
Iranian debts with German companies have been concluded. Iran's 
Deputy Foreign Minister Mahmud Va'ezi told journalists in Tehran 
today that his country originally should have paid 3 billion 
German marks [DM] by 21 March. During his visit to Bonn this 
week, agreement was reached to repay a total of DM4.5 billion by 
the year 2000, beginning 1996. 
  "This is the most comprehensive agreement Iran has ever 
concluded for rescheduling its foreign debts," Va'ezi stated. 
The deputy foreign minister headed an Iranian delegation that 
paid a three-day visit to Germany. He met with Chancellor 
Helmut Kohl and Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel during the visit. 
  According to information from Bonn, Iran is to be granted a 
DM2.5-billion loan by German banks on the basis of commercial 
conditions, which is to be covered by Hermes guarantees. The 
Finance Ministry pointed out Iran's "good values" as far as the 
payment of debts is concerned. The country is currently facing 
liquidity problems because of lower oil prices. 

</TEXT>

