<H3> <TI>   Transportation Ministry Views Swiss Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202093894 Hamburg DPA in German 1317 GMT 21 Feb 94--FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2202093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DPA) -- According to the Federal Government, 
the Swiss referendum for an "Alpine Initiative" that is supposed 
to transfer transit of goods traffic to railroads beginning in 
2004 considerably complicates the Alpine country's negotiations 
with the European Union (EU). As Bonn's Transportation Ministry 
spokesman Veit Steinle reported on Monday [21 February], transit 
traffic is a European problem. The Federal Government realizes 
Switzerland's special traffic situation, but a purely national 
solution cannot be justified. 
  The Transportation Ministry, however, does not think that 
current transit traffic in Switzerland is endangered by the 
referendum. There is a treaty binding under international law 
according to which truck transit has been guaranteed since 1993 
for another 12 years. However, the EU bodies have to deal soon 
with the result of the referendum, it was stated. 
  Michael Mueller, environmental policy spokesman of the 
Social 
Democratic Party [SPD] Bundestag Group, said the result of the 
Swiss referendum is a victory for ecological reason. The SPD 
Group called on the Federal Government to support the "Alpine 
Initiative" and follow it by reorienting its traffic policy. 
The vote also met with agreement from ecologically oriented 
groups. 

</TEXT>

