<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Germany </F>
<H3> <TI>   `No Lasting Improvement' for Labor Market </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402130394 Hamburg DPA in German 1059 GMT 24 Feb 94 -- FOR 
OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2402130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cologne (DPA) -- One out of six Germans willing to 
work will be "affected by underemployment" by the mid-1990's, 
according to the North Rhine-Westphalia Land Labor Office. 
Until then there will be an actual "job gap" for "almost 7 
million persons," Karl Proebsting, president of the Land 
Employment Office, stated in an interview published by the 
Cologne HANDELSMAGAZIN of the Federal Work Group of Medium-Sized 
and Large Retail Trade Companies (BAG). 
  Even under the most favorable economic growth conditions, no 
lasting improvement on the labor market is to be expected for 
the second half of the 1990's. "A consolidation of unemployment 
at an increasingly higher level threatens," he warned. "In 
1995, at the latest, 4 million persons may be unemployed in 
Germany, about 3 million of them in the old laender." In 
addition to this registered unemployment, there is "an enormous 
amount of covert unemployment." On the one hand, it is hidden by 
the use of labor market policy instruments, such as job creation 
measures, qualification, and working short hours; on the other 
hand, more and more people are retreating from the labor market 
because they are discouraged and without prospects. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

