<F P=101> France </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hungarian Prime Minister Meets Government Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Meets Juppe, Balladur </H4>
<F P=102> AU2402130494 Budapest MTI in English 1932 GMT 23 Feb 94 -- 
FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> AU2402130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, 23 February (MTI) -- Hungarian Prime 
Minister Peter Boross on Wednesday [23 February] attended a 
working lunch in the Paris Foreign Ministry and held talks with 
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe on the prospects of 
Hungary's membership in the European Union. 
  Following the talks, Boross told journalists that Hungary 
counts on France understanding its security policy anxieties. 
He said both countries are interested in furthering economic 
integration, and there have been countless signs of political 
rapprochement between the two countries over the past three 
years. 
  Juppe told journalists he considers Hungarian-French 
relations to be excellent, and added that France wishes to 
assist Hungary's efforts to become part of "the European 
family," where he believes Hungary has a place. 
  He said bilateral cooperation is also going well, though 
there is still room for development. 
  Juppe also said that the Bosnian situation was among the 
topics discussed, and that France fully understands the 
difficulties caused for Hungary by the un embargo. "This is one 
more reason for us to find a solution as soon as possible," he 
said. 
  The Hungarian prime minister next held talks with French 
Prime Minister Edouard Balladur in the Matignon Palace. The 
topics discussed were the Bosnian situation and what is commonly 
called "the Balladur plan." 
  In a brief statement to the press about his East-Central 
European stability program, the French prime minister said 
France will do everything possible to ensure East-Central 
European stability. 

</TEXT>

