<H3> <TI>   Senate Speaker Sees Problems for Next Parliament </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2202150394 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1023 GMT 21 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2202150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Spadolini Sees Problems for Next </F>
Parliament"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 21 Feb (ANSA) -- The Italian parliament 
which will be elected March 27 and 28 will have difficulty is 
sustaining a stable government but the drive to restore and 
reinforce the rapport between the political class and the people 
is irreversible, visiting Italian Senate Speaker Giovanni 
Spadolini said here Monday [21 February]. 
  During the press conference which capped his visit, 
Spadolini 
observed "there was the aim to reduce the number of parties, but 
the decision to leave a twenty-five percent share of seats to be 
elected by the proportional system will not simplify the 
position of parties, at least in the next parliament." 
  Nevertheless, the Senate speaker added, the winner-take-all 
constituencies will increase contact between the elected and the 
electors and a candidate will more likely be judged by his 
record, experience and political clout. 
  Turning his attention to the political kickbacks scandal in 
Italy, Spadolini underscored how "this painful affair has shown 
how Italian democracy has the strength to cleanse the errors 
made over past years." 
  The moral question, he added, "...has returned to the center 
of the political life. I had made it the basis of my government 
twelve years ago. I can say now that I was long-sighted and I 
am sure that it will mark the political life in the coming 
years." 

</TEXT>

