<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Italy </F>
<H3> <TI>   Majority Wants Media Law Changed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2302125994 Rome ANSAMAIL Database in English 1543 GMT 22 
Feb 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> BR2302125994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rome ANSAMAIL Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Majority Want Mammi' Law Changed, </F>
Poll Says"] 
  [Text] Milan, 22 Feb (ANSA) -- A majority of Italians want 
to repeal a controversial 1988 broadcasting law which took the 
name of then posts minister Oscar Mammi', according to a Directa 
telephone poll of over 1,000 people taken on February 19-21 in 
76 small, middling and large Italian towns. 
  Posed the question "if there was a referendum to abrogate 
the 
Mammi' law which assigns three TV networks to Silvio 
Berlusconi's group, would you vote to abrogate it or not to 
abrogate it?," 56.4 percent of the sample said they were 
pro-repeal and 43.6 percent anti-repeal. 6.4 percent expressed 
no preference. 
  Directa said the most pro-repeal were males in general (57.3 
percent), 35-to-54-year-olds, and inhabitants of northern and 
central Italy (58.3 percent). 
  It added that the sample is representative of the adult 
population in terms of geographical area, sex, age, and socio- 
professional class. The maximum statistical margin of error was 
estimated at 4 percent. 

</TEXT>

