<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   West Reacts to NATO's Downing of Serb Aircraft </TI></H3>
<H4>   UK Troops on `Heightened Alert' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2802122894 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1204 GMT 28 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2802122894 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Charles Miller, PRESS ASSOCIATION defense correspondent] </F>
  [Text] British forces in Bosnia were today placed on a 
heightened state of alert following the shooting down of four 
Serb aircraft by American warplanes. 
  Military sources described the move as a "sensible 
precaution 
in the light of current circumstances." 
  Work was continuing as normal both on the ground and in the 
air, officials said. 
  There were no British warplanes in the area at the time U.S. 
F-16 Fighting Falcons shot down four Bosnian Serb Galeb attack 
aircraft. 
  The U.S. aircraft, equipped with Sidewinder air-to-air 
missiles, spotted six Galebs in the air close to Banja Luka in 
direct contravention of the UN resolution banning all flights 
over Bosnia. 
  The American pilots ordered the Serb planes to land or be 
shot down. They ignored the warning and four were destroyed. 
  Britain has six Sea Harrier jump-jets, eight Tornado F-3 
fighters and 12 Jaguar strike aircraft flying regular patrols 
over Bosnia. 
  But the Ministry of Defence in London said none were in the 
immediate area when the attack took place. 
  A spokesman said: "Operations are continuing today as 
normal. 
This was a very good example of NATO action in enforcement of a 
UN resolution." 
  Allied aircraft on patrols over Bosnia stay above 10,000ft 
to 
avoid anti-aircraft artillery. 
  The Bosnian Serb forces possess a variety of anti-aircraft 
missiles, including heat-seeking systems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

