<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paris, Washington, Moscow Agree To Intensify Bosnia Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2502192194 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1754 GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2502192194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Paris, Feb 25 (TANJUG) -- Paris, Washington and 
Moscow have fully agreed that "diplomatic contacts be 
intensified" for the soonest possible negotiated settlement in 
the ex-Yugoslav Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, the French 
Foreign Ministry said on Friday [25 February]. 
  The three parties were also completely agreed as to the 
latest initiatives for the resolution of the Bosnian conflict, 
said ministry spokesman Richard Duque. He said this in 
announcing that Foreign Minister Alain Juppe on Thursday night 
talked on the telephone with U.S. State Secertary Warren 
Christopher and Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 
  The spokesman, however, said nothing about France's proposal 
for the U.N. to carry a resolution to place Sarajevo under U.N. 
administration. 
  French media assert this proposal will not easily pass the 
U.N. Security Council, knowing that Moscow apparently disfavours 
it while Washington has not yet made up its mind. 

</TEXT>

