<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Expansion Negotiations Continue in Brussels </TI></H3>
<H4>   No Lowered Fees for Sweden </H4>
<F P=102> LD2602194494 Stockholm Radio Sweden in Swedish 1545 GMT 26 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2602194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Stockholm Radio Sweden </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Swedish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Now to Brussels and the Swedish EU negotiations. 
Less than an hour ago the decisive final negotiations were 
started, and heavy going is expected in the case of the budget, 
where the EU has said no to lowered fees and, instead, is 
offering Sweden an extra sum of money. 
  [Begin recording] [Reporter] It takes two to tango, Swedish 
Minister for Europe Ulf Dinkelspiel said in Brussels today at 
his international news conference. [passage indistinct] 
  Sweden is negotiating with 12 countries who are having their 
own internal games, but today the EU countries were finally 
united on their offers. It is still a clear no to Sweden which 
hoped for a lowered membership fee during the first few years. 
Instead, Sweden is being offered a sum of money which is about 
four million Swedish crowns, less than one-third the rebate 
Sweden was hoping to get. Despite this, Sweden is still the 
country with the best negotiation situation. Is Sweden going to 
sign the deal without the other countries seeking membership, if 
the other candidates stay behind, Minister for Europe Ulf 
Dinkelspiel? 
  [Dinkelspiel] If we reach a satisfactory agreement and both 
parties feel that it is time to sign the agreement, then we will 
sign the agreement. But, our ambition and the ambition of the 
EU is that all candidate countries will be able to conclude at 
practically the same time, and we are going to work towards this 
end. [passage omitted] [end recording] 

</TEXT>

