<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Expansion Negotiations Continue in Brussels </TI></H3>
<H4>   Finnish Talks Reach `Crucial Stage' </H4>
<F P=102> LD2702205194 Helsinki Radio Finland in English 1930 GMT 27 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2702205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Helsinki Radio Finland </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Talks on the terms of Finland's possible 
membership of the European Union [EU] have moved into a crucial 
phase with negotiators in Brussels working to reach settlement 
by midnight Monday [28 February]. According to our 
correspondents in Brussels, positions on the key issue of 
regional supports were still far apart on Sunday. We have this 
report. 
  [Unidentified reporter] It looked on Sunday as if a war of 
nerves was underway in EU membership negotiations in Brussels. 
Finnish representatives and officials of the EU gave the media 
directly conflicting statements on the measure of progress seen. 
The chairman of the EU's Council of Ministers, Theodhoros 
Pangalos, told the press on Sunday afternoon that talks with 
Sweden were the furthest advanced, closely followed by 
discussions with Finland. He stated that he believed that a 
settlement was forthcoming on the tough question of the future 
of Finland's agricultural sector within the EU. 
  In contrast, both Finland's Foreign Minister Heikki Haavisto 
and Foreign Trade Minister Pertti Salolainen said that not much 
ground had been covered on Sunday. Salolainen stated that all 
of the crucial issues were still unresolved and that the EU was 
holding to its previous positions -- stands which Finland has 
declared as unacceptable. Salolainen added that while 
everything possible is being done to ensure the achievement of 
accord on membership terms, Finland is insisting on viable terms. 
  [Announcer] Meanwhile, the Finnish center-right coalition 
cabinet was scheduled to meet late Sunday evening to debate the 
latest results in the membership talks in Brussels. President 
Mauno Koivisto was also expected to sit in on the cabinet 
meeting. 

</TEXT>

