<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   European Union Deliberating Greece-FYROM Dispute </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2602111594 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1000 GMT 26 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2602111594 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Deliberations within the European Union [EU] on the 
countermeasures taken by Greece against Skopje [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] are in progress. German 
Deputy Foreign Minister (Helmut Scheffer) will go to Skopje on 
Monday [28 February] as mediator. British Foreign Secretary 
Douglas Hurd is expected in Athens tomorrow. Furthermore, the 
issue of Skopje is expected to be discussed in Brussels at the 
EU Council of General Affairs. At the same time, EU 
Commissioner for Foreign Affairs Hans van den Broek had a 
telephone conversation with Greek Foreign Minister Karolos 
Papoulias and told him that [FYROM President] Kiro Gligorov's 
regime considers the lifting of the economic sanctions imposed 
by Greece as a necessary precondition for the beginning of the 
process of solving the dispute with Athens. 
  In the meantime, Greek Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's 
answering letter to EU Commission President Jacques Delors and 
the note with Greece's legal arguments to the European 
Commission on the issue were presented yesterday in Brussels. 
  Government Spokesman Evangelos Venizelos stressed that the 
Greek prime minister's answer to Delors is purely political in 
character. Regarding the legal issues raised by Delors, the 
prime minister called attention to the note sent to Brussels by 
the Greek Government. Venizelos stressed that Greece is the 
first to wish for the lifting of the measures as quickly as 
possible, but for this to happen Skopje must give the three 
practical signs of goodwill that have been set demanded by the 
Greek side. 
  Prime Minister Papandreou will brief President Konstandinos 
Karamanlis in the next few days regarding developments on the 
Skopje issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

