<H3> <TI>   Vranitzky: Efforts to Prevent Temelin To Continue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2502201694 Vienna ORF Television Network in German 1830 
GMT 25 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU2502201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Vienna ORF Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Chancellor Franz Vranitzky by Margit </F>
Czoeppan in Vienna on 25 February -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [Czoeppan] Now there is some -- slight -- hope 
that the completion of the Czech nuclear power station in 
Temelin might be prevented. Today the Austrian Temelin 
delegation returned from Washington. The Greens want to 
continue intervention in Washington, while the federal 
chancellor is against the so-called permanent lobbying by the 
Austrian side. There is, however, agreement that the Austrian 
efforts in Washington have had a positive effect. 
  [Vranitzky] They have objectively become better, even though 
one cannot yet say anything for sure at the moment. 
  [Czoeppan] What will happen next? Will Austria pursue a 
kind of permanent lobbying strategy on Temelin? 
  [Vranitzky] Well, it will probably not be permanent 
lobbying, but we will certainly take advantage of the chances 
that we still have, which is why Professor Heindler stayed 
there. As new information comes in, I will decide whether or 
not we will engage in other activities. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

